More straightforward movement variable definitions

Categorize the movement behaviors, and reduce the number of movement behaviors that weâre including

The PCA movement variables are a little hard to interpret, and I want the predictor variables to directly describe aspects of individual behavior/movement/space use.

New proposal is to make a PCA of the strictly movement-related variables, a PC of the strictly roosting-related variables, and then use AKDE home ranges as the third variable measuring space use. Here is what this would look like:

Movement PCA

                PC1    PC2    PC3
mnDailyMnAlt  21.29  65.31  68.49
meanDFD       54.44  14.43 -20.96
meanDMD       52.83 -29.59 -15.72
meanDDT       57.64  14.41 -15.94
mnTort       -21.66  66.66 -66.10

Interpretation

Individuals with higher movement PC1 values fly higher and farther, spend more time flying, and have straighter paths than individuals with lower movement PC1 values. Letâs call this measure just âmovementâ.

Roost behavior PCA

               PC1    PC2    PC3
propSwitch   58.41  53.11 -61.39
shannon      61.44  20.50  76.19
uniqueRoosts 53.04 -82.22 -20.66

Interpretation

Individuals that are higher on the roost PC1 have more unique roosts, a higher roost diversity, and switch roosts more often. Letâs call this a measure of âroost site diversificationâ or something like that.

Correlations

These are still three measures of movement, so I expect that they will be at least somewhat correlated. Letâs take a look!

Movement and roost diversification have a correlation of 0.47.

Roost diversification and log-transformed home range have a stronger correlation of 0.69.

Finally, log-transformed home range and movement have a correlation of 0.47.

There is enough correlation here that weâre going to have to be careful, but I donât think thereâs enough that we have to not proceed. These predictors seem more biologically defensible because they are created a priori instead of derived from a single PCA.
